  "eprint": {
    "title": "Interconnect-Aware Bitstream Modification",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Michail Moraitis",
        "email": "micmor@kth",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Elena Dubrova",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Bitstream reverse engineering is traditionally associated\nwith Intellectual Property (IP) theft. Another, less known,\nthreat deriving from that is bitstream modification attacks. It\nhas been shown that the secret key can be extracted from\nFPGA implementations of cryptographic algorithms by injecting\nfaults directly into the bitstream. Such bitstream modification\nattacks rely on changing the content of Look Up Tables (LUTs).\nTherefore, related countermeasures aim to make the task of\nidentifying a LUT more difficult (e.g. by masking its content).\nHowever, recent advances in FPGA reverse engineering revealed\ninformation on how interconnects are encoded in the bitstream of\nXilinx 7 series FPGAs. In this paper, we show that this knowledge\ncan be used to break or weaken existing countermeasures, as\nwell as improve existing attacks. Furthermore, a straightforward\nattack that re-routes the key to an output pin becomes possible.\nWe demonstrate our claims on an FPGA implementation of\nSNOW 3G stream cipher. The presented results show that there\nis an urgent need for stronger bitstream protection methods.",
    "keywords": [
      "Physical security",
      "SNOW 3G",
      "Stream cipher",
      "Reverse engineering",
      "Bitstream modification",
      "Routing bitstream format"
    ],
